    "<div id=\"evaluation\"></div>\n",
    "\n",
    "### Evaluation of point-based affine image registration\n",
    "\n",
    "<div style=\"float:right;margin:-5px 5px\"><img src=\"assets/question_ico.png\" width=\"42\" height=\"42\"></div> \n",
    "\n",
    "### *Question 2*:\n",
    "Describe how you would estimate the registration error. (Hint: Should you use the same points that you used for computing the affine transformation to also compute the registration error?) How does the number of corresponding point pairs affect the registration error? Motivate all your answers.\n",
    "\n",
    "answer:\n",
    "\n",
    "To estimate the registration error, you compute the Target Registration Error (TRE) by measuring the Euclidean distance between the transformed moving image points and their corresponding points in the fixed image. You should not use the same points for computing the transformation and evaluating the error, because the least-squares fitting minimizes the error on those points by definition, which would give an overly optimistic result. Instead, an independent set of validation points should be used to get a fair estimate of how well the transformation generalizes. Using more point pairs improves the registration accuracy, because the least-squares solution averages out localization noise when the system is overdetermined. However, since an affine transformation in 2D only has 6 degrees of freedom, the improvement diminishes after a certain number of points. The spatial distribution of points across the image is equally important, as evenly spread points ensure the transformation is well-constrained across the entire image."
   ]
  },
